04978nmm a2200721Ia 9780520922099DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t19971997cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209220997 a10.1525/97805209220992doi  a(DE-B1597)649357  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aDR1313.7.A85bS45 1998eb 7aREL0700002bisacsh04a949.7032211 aSells, Michael A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBridge Betrayed :bReligion and Genocide in Bosnia /cMichael A. Sells; ed. by Michael A. Sells. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1997] 4c©1997  a1 online resource (260 p.) :b8 b/w illustrations, 3 tables, 4 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aComparative Studies in Religion and Society0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe recent atrocities in Bosnia-Herzegovina have stunned people throughout the world. With Holocaust memories still painfully vivid, a question haunts us: how is this savagery possible? Michael A. Sells answers by demonstrating that the Bosnian conflict is not simply a civil war or a feud of age-old adversaries. It is, he says, a systematic campaign of genocide and a Christian holy war spurred by religious mythologies.This passionate yet reasoned book examines how religious stereotyping—in popular and official discourse—has fueled Serbian and Croatian ethnic hatreds. Sells, who is himself Serbian American, traces the cultural logic of genocide to the manipulation by Serb nationalists of the symbolism of Christ's death, in which Muslims are "Christ-killers" and Judases who must be mercilessly destroyed. He shows how "Christoslavic" religious nationalism became a central part of Croat and Serbian politics, pointing out that intellectuals and clergy were key instruments in assimilating extreme religious and political ideas.Sells also elucidates the ways that Western policy makers have rewarded the perpetrators of the genocide and punished the victims. He concludes with a discussion of how the multireligious nature of Bosnian society has been a bridge between Christendom and Islam, symbolized by the now-destroyed bridge at Mostar. Drawing on historical documents, unpublished United Nations reports, articles from Serbian and Bosnian media, personal contacts in the region, and Internet postings, Sells reveals the central role played by religious mythology in the Bosnian tragedy. In addition, he makes clear how much is at stake for the entire world in the struggle to preserve Bosnia's existence as a multireligious society.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aGenocidexHistoryx20th centuryxBosnia and Hercegovina. 0aGenocidezBosnia and HercegovinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aGenocidezBosnia and HerzegovinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aMuslimsxHistoryx20th centuryxBosnia and Hercegovina. 0aMuslimszBosnia and HercegovinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aMuslimszBosnia and HerzegovinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aPersecutionxHistoryx20th centuryxBosnia and Hercegovina. 0aPersecutionzBosnia and HercegovinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aPersecutionzBosnia and HerzegovinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aYugoslav War, 1991-1995xAtrocities. 0aYugoslav War, 1991-1995xBosnia and Hercegovina. 0aYugoslav War, 1991-1995xDestruction and pillagexBosnia and Hercegovina. 0aYugoslav War, 1991-1995xDestruction and pillagezBosnia and Hercegovina. 0aYugoslav War, 1991-1995xDestruction and pillagezBosnia and Herzegovina. 0aYugoslav War, 1991-1995zBosnia and Hercegovina. 0aYugoslav War, 1991-1995zBosnia and Herzegovina. 4aChristianity. 4aGeneral. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / General.2bisacsh1 aSells, Michael A., eeditor.4edt4http:/